metadata.name: Schetsboek  #281
metadata.description:
This is my little tribute to fx (hash and fam).

During an important phone call, I was put on hold. Unconsciously, I began to scribble in my sketchbook. Research shows that scribbling helps focusing, but I dreamed away nonetheless until my pages were filled with scribbles, notes, shopping and a to-do list. 

Mint a uniquely generated page from my non-existent 100% coded sketchbook (except text typography). 

The page may contain many scribbles and drawings in pen, felt-tip pen, pencil, or less: often references to artists I admire, some in the form of loose scribbles, others in the form of riddles. Those drawings are drawn with code and vary. Unfortunately, I wasn’t able to incorporate tributes to all art and every artist I admire. The sketchbook would never finish. Thanks to rudxane I know that it’s ok to publish something unfinished ;-). 

One reference that appears in every token is to Sol Lewitt, an incredible source of inspiration. His artworks consist of instructions. Your sketch book pages contain instructions too. You will find the instructions for the artwork scribbled on your unique page by pressing i.

Curious how the work would look without the ‘distracting’ scribbles and coffee stains? Press ‘a’, ‘w’, or ‘g’. 

800 x 800 px

Press ‘s’ to save an image.

Made with p5js and the amazing p5.scribble.js library by Janneck Wullschleger.

Font used: Sacremento-Regular under the SIL Open Font License (OFL).

See license.md for the licenses of both.

Thank you all!

metadata.name: TROUBLEMaker #120
metadata.description:
TROUBLEMaker displays the struggle between two line drawing algorithms, one that wants to paint an ordered radial composition, and another that wants to mess with it. The result is a somehow circular line drawing, which resembles a sort of strange, hand-drawn eye.

This piece is dedicated to my little brother, by messing with all my Lego constructions when we were kids, he thought me more than anybody else about how the interplay of order and chaos is fundamental to creativity and life.

------------------------

Original artwork by Roberto Ranon aka Doble. Made between February and April 2022 using p5.js, canvas-sketch, and love.

The 50% of primary sales is automatically redirected to KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx, a donation smart contract built by FxHash & Versum that supports various ONGs that are helping the people of Ukraine.

May run quite slow on some devices/browsers - in the case, I suggest to use the time to relax and appreciate the animation.

In full screen, pressing Cmd + S or Ctrl + S will save a 4096x4096 image of the artwork.

metadata.name: partition() #191
metadata.description:
This token continuously partitions the canvas, sometimes taking minutes to create tens of thousands of subdivisions. Each token has unique properties that govern partition number and shape, and a random chance to freeze a partition. This allows for a wide variety of outputs, all driven by pure randomness.

Properties describe the entropy of the final output, the final number of partitions, and a rare small chance for filled partitions. This token also has a few interactive features as well (see below).

Software | p5.js
Created  | 11/30/21
Artist   | nicthib

Controls:
1-9: Displays the construction of the piece at each iteration
p: Save a png of the current canvas
s: Save an svg of the current canvas (Note: this can break the live sketch, so reload the page if you want to interact further)
Space: Resets animation
Scroll, click/drag: zoom/pan

metadata.name: Equilibrium #28
metadata.description: Equilibrium shows the algorithm in its search for balance in color and composition. It symbolizes how, at its core, generative art itself is the act of balancing constraints and freedom, consistency and variation, predictability and surprise. Based on empirical data, all mints should eventually converge to a stable state, though this is not guaranteed mathematically. Implemented in 5121 hand-crafted characters of JS code. Forever limited to 100 unique editions living on the Tezos blockchain. London - December 2021.

metadata.name: aether:Astral Loom #185
metadata.description:
Weaving on the astral plane. Lines of transmission. 
Some journeys are straightforward, others yield a multitude of pathways.
Disconnect to interpret.

(As an experiment) the rarity values assigned to this artwork are completely arbitrary, and are in no way connected to the visual output of the minted piece. One might wonder, why have rarity values at all? That's what I ask myself any time I see a value based on rarity attributes instead of viewer aesthetic. 

That being said, I suppose it's up to each person to decide for themselves the value of art...

This artwork was created using p5js.

linktr.ee/lisaorthstudio
twitter: @lisaorthstudio

metadata.name: Euphonic #1301
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moiré effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.
